solution:
Because $\triangle PQR$ is isosceles with $PQ=QR$, median $\overline{QM}$ is also an altitude:


[asy]
size(100);
pair P,Q,R,M,NN;
P = (0,0);
Q = (0.5,0.9);
R = (1,0);
NN = (0.5,0);
M = (Q+R)/2;
draw(rightanglemark(Q,NN,P,2.5));
draw(P--Q--R--P);
draw(Q--NN);
label("$P$",P,SW);
label("$R$",R,SE);
label("$Q$",Q,N);
label("$M$",NN,S);
[/asy]

We have $MP = PR/2 = 16$, so right triangle $PQM$ gives us  \begin{align*}
QM &= \sqrt{PQ^2 - PM^2}\\
&= \sqrt{34^2 - 16^2}\\
&= \sqrt{(34-16)(34+16)}\\
& = \boxed{30}.
\end{align*}  (We might also have recognized that $PM/PQ = 8/17$, so $QM/PQ = 15/17$.)

We draw a regular hexagon and one of its longest diagonals: [asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3)));
[/asy] Now we draw in the other two long diagonals.  We have split the hexagon into six equilateral triangles, which are congruent by symmetry.  [asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3))); draw((1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))); draw((1,sqrt(3))--(0,0));
[/asy] We see that two side lengths make up one long diagonal.  Let the hexagon's side length be $s$, then, its long diagonal has length $2s$ and its perimeter has length $6s$.  The ratio of its long diagonal to its perimeter is hence $\frac{2s}{6s}=\boxed{\frac{1}{3}}$.

